''abacot'' is a word with an interesting history. The common definition given is "an ancient cap of [[slate]] worn by by the [[List of Kings of England|kings of England]], the upper part of which was in the form of a [[double crown]]".

However, the actual word for this item is ''[[bycoket]]''. The initial occurance of ''abacot'' was in Edward Hall's Chronicle of 1548, and occured as a serious misprint. It was copied verbatim by a number of chronicle and dictionary editors over time, and eventually appeared in the 1771 [[Encyclopædia_Britannica|Encyclopædia Britannica]]. The origin of this word was revealed in the Athenaeum in February 1882, by the famous [[Oxford_English_Dictionary|Oxford English dictionary]] editor, [[James_Murray_(lexicographer)|James Murray]].

The chain of mistranscriptions and misprints leading to the "creation" of this word is reputedly :-
 * a bycoket
 * a bicoket
 * abocoket
 * abocoke
 * abacot

